</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,1544,2037]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">
As noted above, this material is from the vicinity of the 
<typeStatus box="[788,836,1545,1569]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">type</typeStatus>
locality (Mt Mlanje, 
<collectingCountry box="[1081,1168,1544,1569]" name="Malawi" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">Malawi</collectingCountry>
) of the distinctive form 
<emphasis box="[151,215,1581,1604]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">crona</emphasis>
, currently treated as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ackery et al. 1995" authorityName="Ackery et al." authorityYear="1995" box="[633,1051,1580,1605]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Monza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="punctata" subSpecies="punctata">
<emphasis box="[633,802,1581,1604]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">M. p. punctata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ackery" box="[820,1043,1580,1605]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" refString="Ackery, P. R., Smith, C. R. &amp; Vane-Wright, R. I. (1995) Carcasson's African Butterflies. An annotated catalogue of the Papilionoidea and Hesperioidea of the Afrotropical Region. CSIRO Publications, Melbourne, Australia, 803 pp." type="book" year="1995">
Ackery 
<emphasis box="[915,967,1580,1605]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[984,1043,1580,1605]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but likely to be a separate valid species (T.B. Larsen pers. comm. 
<number box="[538,599,1616,1640]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="2014.0">2014</number>
). 
<collectionCode box="[619,691,1616,1640]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">TCEC</collectionCode>
found early stages at Ruo Gorge at the foot of Mlanje Mountain, southern 
<collectingCountry box="[255,343,1652,1677]" name="Malawi" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">Malawi</collectingCountry>
, feeding on a large-leaved 
<taxonomicName box="[648,729,1653,1676]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Setaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[648,729,1653,1676]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">Setaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., identified as 
<emphasis box="[929,1111,1652,1677]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName box="[929,1107,1652,1677]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Setaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="grandis">Setaria grandis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Most reports indicate that 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Setaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">S. grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to the Nyika Plateau of northern 
<collectingCountry box="[816,901,1688,1713]" name="Malawi" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">Malawi</collectingCountry>
(e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clayton" box="[981,1143,1688,1713]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" refString="Clayton, W. D. (1989) Setaria grandis Stapf. In: Flora Zambesiaca, 10 (3). Available from: http: // plants. jstor. org / flora / fz 8569 (accessed 9 September 2014)" type="journal article" year="1989">
Clayton 
<number box="[1084,1143,1688,1712]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Golding" box="[1162,1329,1688,1713]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" refString="Golding, J. S. (Ed.) (2002) Southern African plant Red Data Lists. SABONET Report No. 14. Southern African Botanical Diversity Network, Pretoria, South Africa, 256 pp. http: // www. sabonet. org. za / reddatalist / reddatalist _ index. htm" type="book" year="2002">
Golding 
<number box="[1269,1329,1688,1712]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), so this identification may need confirmation. The early stages were found in semi-shade along the road edge, and not on the much more plentiful food plant just outside the forest.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,1544,2037]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">
<collectionCode box="[199,271,1796,1820]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">TCEC</collectionCode>
made observations on the leaf shelters (
<figureCitation box="[719,833,1796,1821]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1322,1344]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,301,1301]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[153,1438,288,1302]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 48. Leaf shelters of Monza punctata punctata on Setaria sp., Ruo Gorge, Malawi [TCEC]. 1, shelter of a young caterpillar, 12 Mar 2014; 2, shelter of a medium-grown caterpillar, 12 Mar 2014; 3, shelter of final instar caterpillar, 12 Mar 2014; 4, pupal shelter, 31 Mar 2014." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251908/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">
Figure 
<number box="[801,833,1796,1820]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="48.0">48</number>
</figureCitation>
). A young caterpillarâ€™s shelter consisted of the midrib and one leaf margin, rolled from the leaf apex back towards the base (Figure 
<number box="[1039,1092,1832,1856]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="48.1">48.1</number>
). A more advanced caterpillar was feeding on both sides of the midrib, but left the leaf margins intact (Figure 
<number box="[1113,1166,1868,1892]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="48.2">48.2</number>
), while the final instar caterpillar ate the leaf out to the margins on both sides, leaving a simple, tightly rolled tubular shelter (Figure 
<number box="[1371,1424,1904,1928]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="48.3">48.3</number>
). A field collected pupa was found in a dead-looking shelter, hanging down as described above for 
<taxonomicName box="[1240,1351,1940,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Monza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alberti">
<emphasis box="[1240,1351,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">M. alberti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Monza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="349">M. cretacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, tightly sealed at each end. The pupal shelter is lined with white waxy powder, but this hardly extends to the pupa (Figure 
<number box="[343,394,2012,2037]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="46.8">46.8</number>
â€“ 
<number box="[410,423,2012,2037]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="9.0">9</number>
, 
<number box="[434,486,2012,2037]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="47.5">47.5</number>
â€“ 
<number box="[502,516,2012,2037]" pageId="48" pageNumber="349" value="6.0">6</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,151,357]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350">
In the Ruo Gorge population, the penultimate instar caterpillars (Figure 
<number box="[1000,1050,152,176]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="49.1">49.1</number>
) have unmarked black heads, with no sign of paler colour, and no indication of black markings on the anal plateâ€”very different in this respect from the 
<taxonomicName box="[196,289,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Chondrolepis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uluguru">Uluguru</taxonomicName>
population. In the final instar, the head is similar to the dark form illustrated from the Udzungwa Mountains, but laterally it is pale brown (Figure 
<number box="[703,757,260,284]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="49.2">49.2</number>
â€“ 
<number box="[772,784,260,284]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="3.0">3</number>
). There seems to be little variability in the head markings of the final instar, unlike 
<taxonomicName box="[451,622,297,320]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Monza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="punctata" subSpecies="punctata">
<emphasis box="[451,622,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="350">M. p. punctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[697,801,295,320]" name="Tanzania" pageId="49" pageNumber="350">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
. The pupa (Figure 
<number box="[1028,1079,296,320]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="49.4">49.4</number>
) is similar to that of the other populations of 
<taxonomicName box="[319,454,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Monza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctata">
<emphasis box="[319,454,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="350">M. punctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figure 
<number box="[550,601,332,357]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="46.8">46.8</number>
â€“ 
<number box="[617,630,332,357]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="9.0">9</number>
, 
<number box="[642,694,332,357]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="47.5">47.5</number>
â€“ 
<number box="[709,723,332,357]" pageId="49" pageNumber="350" value="6.0">6</number>
).
</paragraph>
